<span id="v.iv.ix.x-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="v.iv.ix.x-p1.1"></span>Chapter 10.—</span>18.  Likewise another
Felix of Marazana <span id="fr_1781"></span>[1782](#fn_1781.md) said: 
"There is one faith, one baptism, <span
id="fr_1782"></span>[1783](#fn_1782.md) but of the Catholic Church, to
which alone is given authority to baptize." <span
id="fr_1783"></span>[1784](#fn_1783.md)

<span id="v.iv.ix.x-p5"></span>19.  What if another were to say as
follows:  One faith, one baptism, but of the righteous only, to whom
alone authority is given to baptize?  As these words might be refuted,
so also may the judgment of Felix be refuted.  Do even the unrighteous
who are not <span id="fr_1784"></span>[1785](#fn_1784.md) changed in heart
in baptism, while "they renounce the world in words and not in deeds"
yet belong to the members of the Church?  Let them consider whether such
a Church is the actual rock, the very dove, the bride herself without
spot or wrinkle. <span id="fr_1785"></span>[1786](#fn_1785.md)

